title: For Sale:  Dan Wesson
postcontent: I've got Dan Wesson early 14-2 357 that I am selling.  It's hard to date exactly but I do know it was made between 1968 and 1975 as it is a Monson model with a "pork chop" shroud.  So say these models are more desirable but I have no opinon one way or another.  It's just a damn fine shooting gun and that's all that matters to me.If you don't know the Dan Wesson story, I'd invite you to do some research, the pistol had some really interesting design features that I couldn't do justice if I tried to explain them.  You'll soon see why people like collecting them.The bluing is worn in places and the grips have been replaced however it locks up very tight, the cylindar gap is tiny and the rifling is amazing, especially so for a 40+ year old gun.  It shoots like a dream.  It has the best double action trigger pull of any revolver I've ever shot let alone owned.  The single action trigger is great too.  It's very, very light which may be good or bad depending on your preference.This is a good deal on a great pistol with some innovative features that you cant find anymore.

This is a Beretta 1201FP 12-gauge semi-auto police shotgun with a 20-inch barrel and 6 + 1 capacity.  It has a 3" chamber, a polished chrome-lined bore, a matte hard-chromed bolt, and rifle-style adjustable sights.  The serial number on this one dates it to 1992 manufacture.  It's basically the same shotgun as the Benelli M1 Super 90, but with the Beretta brand and a slightly lower price.  I bought it used a few months ago, and to be on the safe side, used Beretta factory replacements for some of the critical springs:  magazine tube spring, firing pin spring, and hammer spring.  This is an inertia/recoil-operated shotgun (not gas-operated) and is known to have a very reliable action, just like the Benelli.  It's been flawless with everything I've fired through it, including low-recoil/low-velocity shells.  It's in overall very good condition with no rust.  The only detractions are a few scrapes on the left side of the aluminum receiver, likely from a police cruiser shotgun mount.
